<!doctype html>
<html class="no-js" lang="{{ request.locale.iso_code }}" dir="{{ request.locale.direction | default: 'ltr' }}">
  <head>
    {%- comment -%}
      no-js → js class swap. Runs before any <link> so the <head>
      parser paints under `.js` if scripting is on, or stays on
      `.no-js` if the browser has scripting disabled / blocked.
      Lets us style no-JS fallbacks via `html:not(.js) .foo {...}`
      without FOUC. 46 bytes uncompressed; negligible parse cost.

      Inline <script> is justified here (CLAUDE.md "strictly
      necessary") because an external JS would execute AFTER the
      stylesheet is applied — by then the class would have already
      triggered a flash of the no-JS layout on the JS-enabled
      majority of visitors.
    {%- endcomment -%}
    <script>document.documentElement.className='js';</script>
    <meta charset="utf-8">
    <meta http-equiv="X-UA-Compatible" content="IE=edge">
    {%- comment -%}
      `viewport-fit=cover` is required for `env(safe-area-inset-*)`
      to return non-zero values on iPhone X and newer. Without it
      every safe-area declaration in the codebase silently no-ops:
      the cart drawer "Checkout" button hides under the home-bar,
      the search overlay corners clip into the notch, etc. The
      default-without-cover behaviour is to letterbox the page
      inside the safe area, which would also kill any edge-to-edge
      hero design — `cover` is the only sane choice for a modern
      Shopify storefront.
    {%- endcomment -%}
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1, viewport-fit=cover">
    {%- comment -%}
      theme-color — pulls the default color-scheme's surface colour so
      Chrome/Safari paint the address-bar and PWA chrome in the brand
      background instead of defaulting to browser chrome. Falls back
      to the Kitchero brand ivory when the scheme is not yet saved.
    {%- endcomment -%}
    {%- liquid
      assign default_scheme = settings.kt_schemes
      assign theme_color = '#FAFAF9'
      if default_scheme and default_scheme['scheme-1'] and default_scheme['scheme-1'].settings.surface
        assign theme_color = default_scheme['scheme-1'].settings.surface
      endif
    -%}
    <meta name="theme-color" content="{{ theme_color }}">
    <link rel="canonical" href="{{ canonical_url }}">

    {%- comment -%}
      cdn.shopify.com hosts product and section images — the critical
      LCP resource on every storefront page. Pre-connecting here saves
      the DNS + TLS round-trip (~150–300 ms on mobile) before the HTML
      parser discovers the <img>. crossorigin is required because
      Shopify serves image assets as CORS-enabled responses.
    {%- endcomment -%}
    <link rel="preconnect" href="https://cdn.shopify.com" crossorigin>

    {%- comment -%}
      hreflang alternates — one <link> per published locale so Google
      serves the right translation per user locale. Emitted only when
      the shop has more than one published locale; x-default falls back
      to the primary locale.

      The previous implementation hand-built URLs with
      `request.origin + '/' + locale.iso_code + request.path`, which
      double-prefixes on already-prefixed paths (visiting /tr/foo on
      the tr locale would emit /tr/tr/foo for the tr hreflang). Use
      canonical_url + string replace of the CURRENT locale's root_url
      for the TARGET locale's root_url — that stays correct regardless
      of whether the incoming request has a locale prefix or not.
    {%- endcomment -%}
    {%- if shop.published_locales.size > 1 -%}
      {%- assign primary_root = '/' -%}
      {%- for locale in shop.published_locales -%}
        {%- if locale.primary -%}
          {%- assign primary_root = locale.root_url -%}
        {%- endif -%}
      {%- endfor -%}
      {%- for locale in shop.published_locales -%}
        <link rel="alternate" hreflang="{{ locale.iso_code }}" href="{{ canonical_url | replace_first: request.locale.root_url, locale.root_url }}">
      {%- endfor -%}
      <link rel="alternate" hreflang="x-default" href="{{ canonical_url | replace_first: request.locale.root_url, primary_root }}">
    {%- endif -%}

    {%- comment -%}
      PWA / mobile home-screen chrome.

      - icon (32px) for browser tabs.
      - 180px apple-touch-icon for iOS "Add to Home Screen" — without it
        iOS renders a zoomed screenshot of the page, which looks broken.
      - mask-icon for Safari pinned tabs; uses theme-color as its tint.
      - manifest is intentionally omitted (Shopify themes don't ship a
        static /site.webmanifest, and emitting an inline generated
        manifest as a data URL confuses some browsers). iOS + Android
        will fall back to the apple-touch-icon + theme-color when the
        user chooses "Add to Home Screen" — which is the Theme Store's
        expectation for theme-level PWA chrome.

      All branches gate on `settings.kt_favicon` — on a fresh store the
      merchant hasn't uploaded a favicon yet, so we emit nothing rather
      than a broken-link generator output.
    {%- endcomment -%}
    {%- if settings.kt_favicon != blank -%}
      <link rel="icon" type="image/png" href="{{ settings.kt_favicon | image_url: width: 32, height: 32 }}">
      <link rel="icon" type="image/png" sizes="192x192" href="{{ settings.kt_favicon | image_url: width: 192, height: 192 }}">
      <link rel="apple-touch-icon" sizes="180x180" href="{{ settings.kt_favicon | image_url: width: 180, height: 180 }}">
      <link rel="mask-icon" href="{{ settings.kt_favicon | image_url: width: 512, height: 512 }}" color="{{ theme_color }}">
    {%- endif -%}

    {%- unless settings.kt_heading_font.system? and settings.kt_body_font.system? -%}
      <link rel="preconnect" href="https://fonts.shopifycdn.com" crossorigin>
    {%- endunless -%}

    <title>
      {{ page_title }}
      {%- if current_tags %} &ndash; {{ 'kt.meta.tags' | t: tags: current_tags | join: ', ' }}{% endif -%}
      {%- if current_page != 1 %} &ndash; {{ 'kt.meta.page' | t: page: current_page }}{% endif -%}
      {%- unless page_title contains shop.name %} &ndash; {{ shop.name | escape }}{% endunless -%}
    </title>

    {%- comment -%}
      Always emit a description. Fall through page_description
      (per-template override via settings or metafields) → shop.description
      (admin → Preferences) → shop.name, so there is never a missing or
      empty meta description on any storefront page — Google flags the
      "missing description" on sites that skip the tag entirely, and
      social-share scrapers use this field when og:description is absent.
    {%- endcomment -%}
    {%- comment -%}
      Cap meta description at 160 chars — Google's SERP truncates
      around 155-160 chars on desktop and 120 on mobile. A merchant
      who pastes a 300-char marketing paragraph as `shop.description`
      gets it cut mid-sentence in search snippets. `truncate: 160`
      with the ellipsis keeps the visible cut clean and signals to
      crawlers that the description ends gracefully rather than
      being cropped at an arbitrary token.
    {%- endcomment -%}
    <meta name="description" content="{{ page_description | default: shop.description | default: shop.name | escape | truncate: 160, '…' }}">

    {%- comment -%}
      `content_for_header` MUST appear immediately after the title +
      meta-description and BEFORE any theme scripts/stylesheets.
      Shopify docs require this ordering because the injected markup
      carries:
        • analytics + checkout beacons (must run as early as possible),
        • app-installed preload hints (LCP image, critical CSS),
        • hreflang alternates, og/twitter tags, shop extensions.
      Earlier versions of this layout placed the content_for_header
      directive AFTER the global.js + motion vendor scripts, which
      delayed the preload scanner's ability to prioritise hinted
      resources and pushed LCP by 100-300ms on mobile. Moved up per
      Shopify's documented layout spec and the R12 performance
      audit.

      Note: do NOT write literal double-brace or percent-brace
      Liquid markers inside this comment (or any comment). Liquid's
      comment tag does not sandbox embedded output or tag delimiters
      — a stray pair breaks the outer comment's close-match and the
      runtime reports "'comment' tag was never closed" at the parent
      open.
    {%- endcomment -%}
    {{ content_for_header }}

    {% render 'meta-tags' %}

    <script src="{{ 'global.js' | asset_url }}" defer="defer"></script>

    {%- comment -%}
      Motion bundle is ~100 KB unminified (GSAP + ScrollTrigger + Lenis +
      smooth-scroll). Only the marketing-heavy templates actually use it
      — the cart, search, 404, gift-card, customers/*, and policies
      templates do zero scroll animation, so we gate the load behind a
      template whitelist. Shrinks TTI and mobile data usage on the pages
      shoppers hit during the conversion funnel. `request.page_type`
      also covers custom JSON templates the merchant adds later, where
      `template.name` may be a sub-template string like `page.custom`.
    {%- endcomment -%}
    {%- comment -%}
      Motion-vendor trio (GSAP + ScrollTrigger + Lenis + smooth-scroll
      glue) parses and compiles ~325 KB on the main thread. Lighthouse
      consistently flags "Reduce unused JavaScript" on conversion-funnel
      templates that don't run any scroll animation: cart, customers/*,
      policies, password, gift card, 404, captcha. A defer'd script
      doesn't block first paint but it still uses parse + compile +
      cache + bandwidth — Theme Store reviewers running Lighthouse on
      cart.json (a critical conversion path) see the 325 KB hint and
      flag it.

      We tried two approaches before:

        1. Aggressive whitelist (only `index, product, collection,
           list-collections`) — silently broke smooth-scroll and
           dotted-header parallax on `blog, article, page, search,
           404, customers/*`. The user reported regression in
           production; Kitchero's signature scroll feel and the
           parallax dot pattern on journal articles are part of the
           visual identity.

        2. No gate (load everywhere when the setting is on) — fixed
           the regression at the cost of shipping the trio to
           templates that genuinely never scroll-animate.

      Round 13 audit approach: NARROW BLOCKLIST. Skip only the
      templates that have zero merchant-facing animation AND are
      conversion-critical for performance scoring. Long-form content
      (page, blog, article, search) keeps the trio so Lenis +
      parallax stay alive — that was the regression set the user
      reported. Cart / customer / 404 / captcha / gift_card / password
      / policies don't render hero, scroll-pin, or parallax sections,
      so they get the perf win with zero visual impact.

      Theme-check `AssetSizeJavaScript` warnings are silenced because
      these are vendor libraries the user explicitly gated under the
      `kt_motion_reveal` toggle; merchants who care about the perf
      ceiling can disable the toggle outright.
    {%- endcomment -%}
    {%- liquid
      assign load_motion = settings.kt_motion_reveal
      if request.page_type == 'cart' or request.page_type == 'gift_card' or request.page_type == 'password' or request.page_type == '404' or request.page_type == 'captcha' or request.page_type == 'policy'
        assign load_motion = false
      endif
      if request.page_type contains 'customers/'
        assign load_motion = false
      endif
    -%}
    {%- if load_motion -%}
      {%- comment %}theme-check-disable AssetSizeJavaScript{% endcomment -%}
      <script src="{{ 'vendor-gsap.js' | asset_url }}" defer="defer"></script>
      <script src="{{ 'vendor-scrolltrigger.js' | asset_url }}" defer="defer"></script>
      <script src="{{ 'vendor-lenis.js' | asset_url }}" defer="defer"></script>
      <script src="{{ 'smooth-scroll.js' | asset_url }}" defer="defer"></script>
      {%- comment %}theme-check-enable AssetSizeJavaScript{% endcomment -%}
    {%- endif -%}

    {%- render 'kt-css-variables' -%}

    {{ 'base.css' | asset_url | stylesheet_tag }}
    {%- comment -%}
      Loader CSS is ~10 KB and only styles an overlay that appears when
      the merchant has enabled `kt_loader_enable` in Theme Settings.
      Gating the stylesheet behind the same toggle skips the request
      entirely on stores that have the intro loader disabled — direct
      LCP/FCP win without touching the JS bootstrap (which does its
      own `loaderEnabled` check below).
    {%- endcomment -%}
    {%- if settings.kt_loader_enable -%}
      {{ 'kt-loader.css' | asset_url | stylesheet_tag }}
    {%- endif -%}

    {%- comment -%}
      Drawer / overlay CSS — loaded in <head> so the stylesheet
      applies before first paint. These files are small (5-10KB
      each) and only render work when the drawer opens, so the
      parser-blocking cost is negligible. Previously emitted in
      <body> with `media="print" onload="this.media='all'"` async-
      swap, but the onload handler didn't fire reliably across
      CSP / extension combos and left the cart drawer unstyled:
      opened drawer rendered full-width instead of a right-side
      panel. <head>-loaded `stylesheet_tag` guarantees application.
    {%- endcomment -%}
    {%- if settings.kt_cart_type == 'drawer' -%}
      {{ 'kt-cart-drawer.css' | asset_url | stylesheet_tag }}
    {%- endif -%}
    {{ 'kt-search-overlay.css' | asset_url | stylesheet_tag }}
    {{ 'kt-appointment-drawer.css' | asset_url | stylesheet_tag }}

    {%- comment -%}
      Resource hints — Shopify Theme Store performance rule (PRF-3):
      "You can add up to two resource hints to your code per template."
      Reduced from 5 conditional preloads (body, body-bold, heading,
      accent, localization-form CSS) to a hard cap of 2: body regular
      + heading. These two faces are the LCP-critical paint
      (most pages render their hero/H1 with heading, body copy with
      kt_body_font). The bold body weight, accent font, and
      localization stylesheet are all below-fold or conditional —
      kt-css-variables.liquid already emits their @font-face with
      font-display: swap, so they load lazily without FOUT when the
      first character of that face is needed. Trading a small CLS
      hint for a Theme Store reviewer-mandated cap.
    {%- endcomment -%}
    {%- unless settings.kt_body_font.system? -%}
      {% comment %}theme-check-disable AssetPreload{% endcomment %}
      <link rel="preload" as="font" href="{{ settings.kt_body_font | font_url }}" type="font/woff2" crossorigin>
      {% comment %}theme-check-enable AssetPreload{% endcomment %}
    {%- endunless -%}
    {%- unless settings.kt_heading_font.system? -%}
      {% comment %}theme-check-disable AssetPreload{% endcomment %}
      <link rel="preload" as="font" href="{{ settings.kt_heading_font | font_url }}" type="font/woff2" crossorigin>
      {% comment %}theme-check-enable AssetPreload{% endcomment %}
    {%- endunless -%}

    {%- if localization.available_countries.size > 1 or localization.available_languages.size > 1 -%}
      {%- comment -%}
        Localization stylesheet was previously preloaded — counted
        as a 5th resource hint. Now lazy-loaded via plain
        stylesheet_tag (no preload kw), saving the hint slot for
        body+heading fonts above. The selector is below-fold in
        the footer (mobile drawer is opened on demand) so async
        load is acceptable.
      {%- endcomment -%}
      {{ 'kt-localization-form.css' | asset_url | stylesheet_tag }}
      <script src="{{ 'localization-form.js' | asset_url }}" defer="defer"></script>
    {%- endif -%}

    <script>
      if (Shopify.designMode) {
        document.documentElement.classList.add('shopify-design-mode');
      }
    </script>

    {%- comment -%}
      Loader bootstrap: decides — before first paint — whether to skip
      the intro loader. Added here (not in kt-loader.js) because the JS
      file is deferred and by the time it runs the loader would already
      have flashed visible. Adds a class to <html> so CSS can hide the
      loader with `display: none` from the very first paint.
    {%- endcomment -%}
    <script>
      (function () {
        try {
          var loaderEnabled = {{ settings.kt_loader_enable | json }};
          if (!loaderEnabled ||
              sessionStorage.getItem('kitchero:loader-shown') ||
              (window.Shopify && Shopify.designMode)) {
            document.documentElement.classList.add('kt-loader-skip');
          }
        } catch (e) {
          /* Private mode / storage blocked — show the loader anyway. */
        }
      })();
    </script>
    <script src="{{ 'kt-loader.js' | asset_url }}" defer="defer"></script>
  </head>

  <body class="gradient" data-kt-scheme="{{ settings.kt_schemes.first.id }}" data-cart-type="{{ settings.kt_cart_type | default: 'drawer' }}">
    {%- render 'kt-loader' -%}

    <a class="skip-to-content-link button visually-hidden" href="#MainContent">
      {{ 'kt.a11y.skip_to_text' | t }}
    </a>

    {%- comment -%}
      Global assertive + polite announcer regions. Any part of the
      theme can push a message by writing to `#ktAnnouncer` (polite,
      non-interrupting: filter/sort updates, ATC success, share
      copied) or `#ktAnnouncerAlert` (assertive: validation errors,
      destructive-action confirmations). Hidden visually but read
      out to assistive tech.

      Why a GLOBAL live region and not per-section ones: SRs don't
      reliably announce newly-inserted aria-live regions — the region
      has to pre-exist and only its textContent change. Keeping two
      persistent regions (polite + assertive) means a drawer or
      section that swaps its DOM out can still emit announcements
      without losing them in the transition.
    {%- endcomment -%}
    {%- comment -%}
      `role="status"` implies `aria-live="polite"` by default, and
      `role="alert"` implies `aria-live="assertive"`. Declaring both
      is redundant ARIA — axe-core flags `aria-redundant` and some
      SRs double-announce. Keep the roles (clearer semantics) and
      drop the implied live values.
    {%- endcomment -%}
    <div
      id="ktAnnouncer"
      class="visually-hidden"
      aria-atomic="true"
      role="status"
    ></div>
    <div
      id="ktAnnouncerAlert"
      class="visually-hidden"
      aria-atomic="true"
      role="alert"
    ></div>

    {%- comment -%}
      Drawer / overlay MARKUP. The stylesheets themselves load in
      <head> (above) so the panels are already styled when they
      render. Markup kept in <body> so it lives inside the layout
      flow (and so `{% section 'cart-drawer' %}` participates in
      the Section Rendering API for AJAX refresh).
    {%- endcomment -%}
    {%- if settings.kt_cart_type == 'drawer' -%}
      {% section 'cart-drawer' %}
    {%- endif -%}
    {%- render 'search-overlay' -%}
    <script src="{{ 'search-overlay.js' | asset_url }}" defer="defer"></script>
    {%- render 'appointment-drawer' -%}
    <script src="{{ 'appointment-drawer.js' | asset_url }}" defer="defer"></script>

    {% sections 'header-group' %}

    <main id="MainContent" class="content-for-layout focus-none" tabindex="-1">
      {%- comment -%}
        Global breadcrumb — single render at the top of `<main>`,
        following Shopify's official liquid-code-examples pattern.
        snippets/breadcrumbs.liquid filters out page types where a
        breadcrumb adds no value (index, cart, list-collections, 404,
        password, gift_card, customer/*). One render here keeps the
        navigation aid consistent across every product, collection,
        article, blog, page (default + alt-template), and search
        result — no template-by-template wiring, no inconsistency
        when a custom layout (banner-cover hero, etc.) skips the
        main-* section that previously hosted the breadcrumb.

        Merchants who want a quieter site can flip
        `settings.kt_show_breadcrumbs` off in Theme Settings.
      {%- endcomment -%}
      {%- if settings.kt_show_breadcrumbs -%}
        <div class="page-width kt-breadcrumbs-wrap">
          {%- render 'breadcrumbs' -%}
        </div>
      {%- endif -%}

      {{ content_for_layout }}
    </main>

    {% sections 'footer-group' %}

    {%- comment -%} Structured Data (JSON-LD) {%- endcomment -%}
    {%- render 'structured-data' -%}

    <ul hidden>
      <li id="a11y-refresh-page-message">{{ 'kt.a11y.refresh_page' | t }}</li>
      <li id="a11y-new-window-message">{{ 'kt.a11y.link.new_window' | t }}</li>
    </ul>

    <script>
      // Bootstrap the Kitchero runtime namespace. `global.js` (loaded with
      // defer) adds focusTrap / bus / escapeCloseDetails to the same object,
      // so the `|| {}` guard lets either script run first.
      window.Kitchero = window.Kitchero || {};

      {%- liquid
        assign search_types = ''
        if settings.kt_search_inc_products
          assign search_types = search_types | append: 'product,'
        endif
        if settings.kt_search_inc_pages
          assign search_types = search_types | append: 'page,'
        endif
        if settings.kt_search_inc_articles
          assign search_types = search_types | append: 'article,'
        endif
        if settings.kt_search_inc_collections
          assign search_types = search_types | append: 'collection,'
        endif
        assign search_types = search_types | split: ',' | join: ','
      -%}
      {%- comment -%}
        Every value interpolated into this JS blob is emitted via
        `| json` so Shopify produces a fully JS-string-literal-safe
        value (with surrounding double quotes). This closes two
        injection vectors:

        1. Single-quoted strings: a variant title / route with `'` in
           it would otherwise break out.
        2. Backtick template literals: a translation containing
           `${...}` would otherwise be parsed as a JS expression
           (merchant-localized strings can easily carry `$`).

        Shopify `| json` produces proper JSON, which is itself valid
        JS syntax for strings / numbers — no extra quoting needed on
        our side.
      {%- endcomment -%}
      Object.assign(window.Kitchero, {
        shopUrl: {{ request.origin | json }},
        routes: {
          cartAdd:          {{ routes.cart_add_url | json }},
          cartChange:       {{ routes.cart_change_url | json }},
          cartUpdate:       {{ routes.cart_update_url | json }},
          cart:             {{ routes.cart_url | json }},
          predictiveSearch: {{ routes.predictive_search_url | json }},
          {%- comment -%}
            `search` was missing here; predictive-search.js's "press
            Enter to search anyway" path was hardcoding `/search`,
            which 404s on multi-locale storefronts where the locale
            prefix is required (e.g. `/de/search`). `routes.search_url`
            resolves to the correct localized path on every Market.
          {%- endcomment -%}
          search:           {{ routes.search_url | json }},
        },
        searchSettings: {
          {%- comment -%}
            Placeholder convention — pass `[count]` / `[subtotal]` as
            the `| t:` argument so the rendered string has a JS-
            replaceable token (square brackets). We previously used
            Liquid-style curly-brace placeholders (count in double
            braces) which collide with Liquid's own tag syntax:
            Shopify's parser greedy-matches the closing double-brace
            from INSIDE the nested string and closes the outer filter
            tag early, spilling raw Liquid source into the page → a
            JS SyntaxError when browsers encounter the opener in
            script. Square-bracket placeholders dodge the syntax
            conflict entirely and follow Skeleton's placeholder
            convention. Also: keep this comment free of literal
            double-brace sequences — Liquid comment tags do NOT
            sandbox embedded output delimiters from the parser, and
            a stray pair inside a comment will be reported as an
            unclosed comment tag at the line of the outer open.
          {%- endcomment -%}
          types:               {{ search_types | json }},
          resultsAnnouncement: {{ 'kt.search.results_announcement' | t: count: '[count]' | json }},
          noResults:           {{ 'kt.search.no_results_announcement' | t | json }}
        },
        cartStrings: {
          error:           {{ 'kt.cart.cart_error' | t | json }},
          quantityError:   {{ 'kt.cart.cart_quantity_error_html' | t: quantity: '[quantity]' | json }},
          updatedSubtotal: {{ 'kt.cart.updated_subtotal' | t: subtotal: '[subtotal]' | json }},
        },
        variantStrings: {
          addToCart:      {{ 'kt.product.add_to_cart' | t | json }},
          addSubscription: {{ 'kt.product.add_subscription_to_cart' | t | json }},
          addedToCart:    {{ 'kt.product.added_to_cart' | t | json }},
          addToCartError: {{ 'kt.product.add_to_cart_error' | t | json }},
          soldOut:        {{ 'kt.product.sold_out' | t | json }},
          unavailable:    {{ 'kt.product.unavailable' | t | json }},
          subscriptionUnavailable: {{ 'kt.product.subscription_unavailable' | t | json }},
        },
        a11yStrings: {
          imageAvailable: {{ 'kt.product.media.image_available' | t: index: '[index]' | json }},
          shareSuccess:   {{ 'kt.share.success_message' | t | json }},
        }
      });
    </script>

    {%- if settings.kt_cart_type == 'drawer' -%}
      <script src="{{ 'cart-drawer.js' | asset_url }}" defer="defer"></script>
    {%- endif -%}

    {%- if settings.kt_search_predictive -%}
      <script src="{{ 'predictive-search.js' | asset_url }}" defer="defer"></script>
    {%- endif -%}
  </body>
</html>
